# Transactions

Use `prisma.$transaction` when multiple writes must succeed or fail together.

## When required

- Register user + default role + audit log
- Password reset + revoke sessions + audit log
- Email verify + update user + audit log
- Any multi-table mutation with business invariants

## Pattern

```typescript
await prisma.$transaction([
  prisma.user.update({ where: { id }, data: { passwordHash } }),
  prisma.session.updateMany({ where: { userId: id }, data: { revokedAt: new Date() } }),
  prisma.auditLog.create({ data: { userId: id, action: AuditAction.PASSWORD_RESET_COMPLETED, ...meta } }),
]);
```

## Interactive transactions

Use callback form when later steps depend on earlier results:

```typescript
await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  const user = await tx.user.create({ data });
  await tx.auditLog.create({ data: { userId: user.id, action: "REGISTER" } });
  return user;
});
```

## Rules

- Keep transactions short — no external API calls inside
- Handle unique constraint failures → `409`
- Avoid long-held transactions under load

## Read + write

For read-then-write race conditions, use unique constraints or `updateMany` with conditions rather than blind read-modify-write.
